---
description: Name caught throwables $exception, never $e
globs: "**/*.php"
alwaysApply: false
---

# Exception / throwable variable names

- In `catch` clauses and parameters that hold a `Throwable`/`Exception`, use **`$exception`** (or a domain-specific name such as `$previous` when chaining).
- **Do not** use **`$e`** for exception variables—prefer readable, self-documenting names.

```php
// Bad
} catch (\Throwable $e) {
    $this->log->error($e->getMessage());
}

// Good
} catch (\Throwable $exception) {
    $this->log->error($exception->getMessage());
}
```

Private helpers that accept a caught instance should use the same convention: `function handleFailure(\Throwable $exception): void`.
